posts.title: The drone shit is obviously our government fam. They all have the FAA required lighting that typically pulses 40-100 times a minute.
posts.content:
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) has established specific requirements for aircraft lighting to ensure safety during operations, particularly at night. Here's a summary of the requirements related to blinking lights:

Aircraft Lights (Position Lights): According to 14 CFR § 91.209, no person may operate an aircraft from sunset to sunrise (or during specified conditions in Alaska) unless it has lighted position lights. These lights consist of a red light on the left wingtip, a green light on the right wingtip, and a white light on the tail.

Anti-collision Lights: Aircraft equipped with an anti-collision light system must have these lights operational during all types of operations, day and night, unless the pilot-in-command determines that turning them off would be in the interest of safety due to specific operating conditions. The anti-collision light system can include rotating beacons or strobe lights, which can be either red or white.

Flashing Rate: For anti-collision lights, the system should flash between 40 to 100 times per minute as per 14 CFR 25.1401.

Drones: For drones or unmanned aircraft systems, under Part 107 regulations, anti-collision lights (which are blinking/strobing) are required for night operations to ensure visibility for three statute miles
